Enforces that retired terminology (identifiers deemed obsolete by ADRs) appears only in history and audit documents, never in live code, docs, or prompts — preventing stale concept names from poisoning the next context reseed.

The script searches all tracked and untracked-not-ignored files via `git ls-files`, excluding `.context/` (regenerated by ctx-scan, not hand-edited) and whitelisted paths: `docs/DECISIONS.md`, `docs/retired/**`, `docs/AUDIT.md`, `docs/OPUS_CONTEXT_FRESHNESS_PROMPT.md`, and this script itself. The `BANNED` array lists retired terms — currently `ctx-access`, `init-task`, `end-task`, `served_nodes`, `SPEC.md`, `CTX_AGENT_MODEL` — and is appended whenever an ADR retires an identifier.

Each violation is reported as `FAIL: path:line:content -- retired identifier, see docs/DECISIONS.md…` with the grep output unprefixed to preserve the `path:line` form that ctx-verify's `split_loc` parser expects; the explanatory suffix after the matched content is safe and intended for downstream tooling.